      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay thanks. that makes more sense. so after they get pulled to the poles, what happens in telophase? how do the two new cells actually form?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In telophase, the final stage of mitosis, the chromatids that have been pulled to opposite poles of the cell begin to decondense, returning to their less tightly coiled state. The nuclear envelope, which had broken down during earlier phases, starts to reform around each set of chromosomes, creating two distinct nuclei within the cell. This is akin to two separate kingdoms emerging from a single realm. Meanwhile, the spindle fibers disassemble, and the cell prepares for the final act of division. The cytoplasm begins to divide, a process known as cytokinesis, which ultimately results in the formation of two new, genetically identical daughter cells. Each daughter cell enters into interphase, the period of growth and DNA replication, ready to begin the cycle anew.",
